,Recommended,302270,11365239,"Posted: 22 July, 2014",all,Spero,"(My recommendation of this game is conditional, read the conclusion at the bottom)This is basically a tweaked version of Dungeon Defenders with a new infrastructure for online play called Playverse. So what’s good about it?The Good:There are some cool new features like Dash, Extra Spells from Items, Armor Asthetics, etc. All of these features are very much welcomed and are pretty fun. I do enjoy dropping down a lightning storm on a large group of minions that are knocking at the walls from an amulet I picked up. You can check out the features on the DD Eternity Website.Playverse seems to add more tools for online play. Also it’s probably the main reason for Eternity as it’s what Trendy plans to use for cross platform play, which seems pretty cool.At the time of this review I have only played to level 15, so I can’t speak too much for balance and security, but according to Trendy the items and are more balanced and the game has more protection from hacking (Most likely since it’s ran through Playverse).The Bad:As many have said, “No solo play”, at least I can’t find it. Trendy should realize some people like to test their skills solo and not be bothered by people using up all the defense points in poor ways or just getting in the way.Tooltips, Tooltips, Tooltips. How something so simple and prevalent in modern software seems to have eluded Trendy. There are tooltips but a lot of the new UI and the Playverse are missing these for a number of things.This leads me to documentation. There’s no help or anything explaining all the new things like Crafting, Dyes, Why do I start with 4 characters I did not create with numbers in their names, etc.You can't hide armor, or at least I can't find the option. There are some pretty cool costumes and it kind of sucks that you can't hide some ugly helmet with good stats that covers up a cool visor from your costume.When an inventory screen(like merchant or forge) and your mouse is over an item to read the description, if somebody walks past your mouse the description goes away and you have to move the mouse back and forth to get it back. Maybe a minor gripe, but something they should fix since taverns can be a bit chaotic.Notes:There are Micro-Transactions, though they are for aesthetic items only. Currently there are some problems with joining games, though Trendy is aware of it and working on it. Only happened once to me, I just retried once and it worked. The tavern is not private, which doesn't bother me, but may bother some. It's probably like that to make the game more social. This is basically treated as a new game, so you will be starting from scratch with a new hero. Previous dungeon defender one heroes will not be available.Conclusion:If you want to play Dungeon Defenders online, with more balance, security, some interesting new features and the above listed limitations (mostly no solo play, hopefully they’ll add itThey Did!) then I’d pick this up on a good sale. Otherwise wait for Dungeon Defenders 2 and play the previous one.Edit:Trendy has now enabledprivate sessions. When starting a level you can now select host private session. Also through the Playverse overlay (F11) you can then invite people to it."
