76561198018254117,Not Recommended,302270,11841351,"Posted: 23 August, 2014",all,cmcfsc2000,"Trendy does what they want and cares nothing for their customers & fans.  Long story short: This is a game that's being marketed as ""definitive"" that's in an early beta phase, at best.  There's rollbacks and lag issues for their online-only servers (there's no offline mode), a complete lack of meaningful loot progression, horrible UI issues (it looks like it was made to fit in mobile, and there's annoyances like item stats not being on dedicated lines so it's hard to compare items), and there's a HUUUUGGEEE list of features that existed in DD1 that don't in DDE.Things missing:1) Nightmare mode, hardcore mode, mixed mode, and pure strategy mode.2) Full Single Player functionality - They added single player after the community outcry, and have been slowly adding in more and more functionality, but it's not quite there yet3) Private taverns - You're stuck in a communal tavern with 15 other people happily making tons of noise.  If you dislike hearing Slice 'n' Dices attack dummies or simply don't want to read a 13y/o's curse-heavy ranting, or simply want to decorate your own private tavern, then you're out of luck.4) No achievements/awards/trophies - With the conversion over to public tavern, all the joys of trophies in private taverns are gone.  There's nothing to work towards, and no reason to beat any maps besides the ones that give loot.5) Challenge rewards - Currently, challenges provide ZERO experience and loot.  Upon completion, they DO give artifacts, which are permanent stat boosters, but these artifacts are not stackable and offer completely negligible increases (we're talking adding 8hps to a character with 10-20k life, and 1-2 to fire resist when you have 950).6) Loot despawning priorities - In DD1, loot has prioritization on what disappears first.  In DDE, it doesn't.  And there's FAR fewer items allowed on the ground (online server reasons?).  Currently, instead of the ~200 items allowed in DD1 on bigger maps, there's 35 allowed in DDE, and because there's no loot despawn prioritization, that means stuff often disappears before it hits the ground.  Loot only appears near you, and even when it does that upgrade that just dropped might disappear before you can get to it while the 50g item you can buy from the tavernkeeper sticks around for 10 minutes.7) Meaningful progression and incentive to do hard maps - Everyone does insane ramparts.  Why?  Because it drops far better loot than any of the DLC or later maps like CD, and it's one of the easiest maps in the game.  Of course, this means that once you get the gear from ramparts, there's nothing else to do, so the playerbase has dropped by half every 1.5-2 weeks since release.8) Tower/Character balance - DD1 didn't have great balance, but it at least didn't have completely broken classes.  Huntress traps are so bad that no one uses them, summoner pets are broken (either useless or so OP they break their own animation with how fast they shoot), towers get over-nerfed for no reason and in an odd manner (including nerfs to huntress traps no one uses), and some classes are flat-out bad now (barbarian is HORRIBLE).9) Itemization - Some great items from DD1 are missing (treadmill pets, costumes that change gameplay mechanics, meaningful & unique weapons), and the itemization in general is just inferior.  Weapons are all very similar and no longer have speed stats, so they all basically feel the same (outside of huntress, who has a few weps that are clearly superior, especially with the removal of speed stats).  Monk weapons all have horrible ranged damage so ranged monk dps isn't viable, barbarian swords are junk (speed stat issue again causing problems, to say nothing of barbarian stat scaling itself), apprentice weapons are all similar and junky enough that apprentice DPS isn't really a thing, etc.10) Rewards for the challenges/campaign maps/survivals - There's no rewards for any of these, including beating CD.  You get... nothing.  no seahorses, no pets, no specific weapons dropping from specific bosses... nothing unique.  everything that drops drops everywhere, and while some campaign maps like aquanos will reward you after beating a boss, the rewards are completely random... you can get a few accessories and nothing else.11) A whole MESS of maps, costumes, pets, items, and other fun things that simply don't exist in DDE.  Too many to count or list here.12) a workable armor set system - DDE has a few extra slots for armor and 9 different sets instead of 4.  I'm too lazy to do the math, but instead of sets being fairly viable for everyone, at any level, they're now basically inaccessible to most of the community, since the chances of you having the same 1 (out of 9) type of item for all 7 slots that's decent enough to wear is nigh impossible.13) A balanced upgrading system - The new system is percentage-based, and it's FAR harder to get money for those upgrades.  You'll have to spend a LOT of time playing Vacuum Simulator, since smashing the ""E"" key and picking up everything to sell it later is the only decent way to get money.  But even that aside, the percentage-based system (10% of base stats per upgrade, and 20% of base damage per) completely breaks itemization.  I won't go into detail, but suffice to say this breaks endgame items and throws items (and thus, characters) completely out of balance.14) Kick system - If you like playing public games, accept that about half the players you encounter will simply afk the second they join the game, and there's nothing you can do about it.  At all.  And that's if you're lucky... if you're not they can actively ruin your experience by selling your towers, and again, there's nothing you can do about it.Basically, I could go on for paragraphs on content that's in DD1 that was simply left out or is plain better (UI, loot despawn code, loot progression, trophies, map rewards, etc etc etc), but here's what it all boils down to:  you are NOT getting a definitive version of DDE.  You're buying what everyone playing agrees is a beta product.  I didn't even list out the major bugs & exploits in the game, and there's a LOT.  So while this game has a few improvements (more active play options with amulets, a conceptually better survival mode), none of it is balanced yet and there's so many bugs and issues in the game that you shouldn't give Trendy money for a ""definitive edition"" when it's nowhere near that state.  Some people might still like the game and play it, but no one can argue with the fact that this is a works-in-progress, so ask yourself if you want to reward a company that essentially spits on their best customers by re-releasing a title like this in such a misleading fashion.At best, hold on to your money until the game is what they say it is, and frankly, I don't think it ever will be.  The core of DDE is so busted that even when they DO tack on NM, it's certainly not going to FIX anything... it'll just magnify the problems that already exist and aren't being addressed."
