,Recommended,302270,11439546,"Posted: 27 July, 2014",all,MrEvilDr,"Not sure why this is getting such bad reviews. This is everything Dungeon Defenders 1 was, and more! Player instanced loot and chests are an amazing addition, saving the grief from ninja looters in public games. Plus, currency is Gold instead of Mana, meaning you can spam your Mana in-game without having to worry about the cost. Blueprints are available as drops for crafting which is aother great feature. The micro-transactions in-game are strictly for cosmetic items, but that's to be expected in this day of Microtransactions. A lot of complaints were also targetted at the fact that you apparently can't create Private games, which isn't true. It may be a recent addition, but since I bought the game there is an option to create a private game just for you and your friends - You're not forced to play with random players. For £4.50 for Dungeon Defenders 1 owners, it's well worth it. It's just a fresh take on the game with some great additions, balance and bug fixes.The negatives are the fact that the game features it's own Always-Online DRM, meaning you're relying on their servers for a good connection - I'm used to this having played Diablo III for a long time. Plus, the UI is a clunky and could do with some work here and there, but it's nothing game-breaking.Don't let all of the overracting negative reviews put you off, I'm sure glad I didn't. The game has been out for 5 days, there are still some fixes they have to make and they're working fast. I have faith!This game will definitely whet my appetite until Dungeon Defenders 2 comes out, and I'm pretty sure they have a few more features still to come!"
