76561197994547714,Recommended,302270,11380412,"Posted: 23 July, 2014",all,Esthrus,"After playing Dungeon Defenders Eternity for a bit, I can see what other reviewers have been concerned about. While I echo some of these concerns, others I do not.First and foremost, many have said that the game should not be purchased due to lack of single player mode. That has been rectified, and I have played through the first level on a couple of different difficulties by myself with a couple of characters, and can confirm that this mode is working fine. Trendy had thought that their server costs might be too high if they immediately allowed single player, and quickly backed off due to the backlash over not having the mode. While it should have shipped with the mode enabled, I was pleased that they quickly rectified the situation.I will note, however, that all play is online and requires you to establish a separate account. This is both good and bad, as, while it does require you to always have an internet connection, it also allows you to continue your characters across devices. More devices, such as androids and iPads, should be coming in the near future, and I'm quite excited about that feature, especially assuming I can keep my characters.The second point, I think, is the primary cause for concern, and that is micropayments. Currently a number of specialized emotes can be purchased for $1 each in the store, amounting to a total of $30ish. This would bring the cost of the game to over $50 if one were to purchase all of them, but I sincerely doubt one would. Of course, being emotes, these are hardly necessary to beat the game mercilessly. However, it does open the door for other microtransactions. The store is far from fully stocked, and I expect that we will see more items that require real money soon. That said, Trendy has stated that DD2 will not be pay to win, and I expect that this game won't be either.Those are the main concerns I've seen from people, Now on to the features. So far I really like the rebalance, and I LOVE the visible armor, consumables, and general polish that the game seems to have. It feels like a nice update to the original Dungeon Defenders. There weren't any features I felt were missing, and progression so far has felt very smooth. I was most pleased, I think, that I found a few of the items that were harder to find in the original DD, such as pets and belts, immediately. I haven't felt like I wasn't getting the gear I needed, and I think Trendy has made sure that the loot progression feels a little more fluid than it did in DD, where I admittedly got stuck in the 70s. I can only hope that this trend continues.Overall, I would say that DDE is a nice update to DD that doesn't entirely deserve the criticism currently being levied at it. Time will tell if the game will continue to live up to my high regard for Trendy after the beauty that was the original Dungeon Defenders, but I'm confident that they have it in them to do what's right here."
,Recommended,302270,11379959,"Posted: 23 July, 2014",all,mo0cat,"I LOVE this game. Of couse I'm biased because I also loved DD1, this is essentially Dungeon Defenders 1 version 2.0, packaged up and rereleased as a separate game to resolve some issues that might have come up with making secure servers and whatnot. One of the issues I've seen with other reviews is the removal of single play as well as private play, but that was fixed the day of release, and seeing as it was an advertised feature before I bought it, I didn't mind waiting a couple of hours to play exclusively with two of my friends.The two 'issues' I have with the game are microtransactions, while they are exclusively cosmetic, I would like them to become unlocks that come with achievement like activities, like the skins; and no achievements, what's up with that?Overall this is a great deal, especially if you enjoyed the first(returning steam customers only pay $6 for the full game, as well as most DLC released, currently around... $50?) and new customers looking to get into the game, this is a wonderful opportunity to do so, I can't wait to play more and explore the new features and balances."
