76561197968329361,Recommended,302270,11400517,"Posted: 25 July, 2014",all,Ghost Requiem,"Long time Dungeon Defender players may raise an eyebrow or two at Dungeon Defenders Eternity. At best it seems like a light DLC at the current discounted price for previous owners ($6 USD). It includes a few new maps, a new consumable system, rebalance of classes (summoner being one of the bigger changes), and a new patching system which requires an online connection to play single player. Players can also play crossplatform with this version. There's also a built in cash shop in the game and for the time being, it only contains cosmetic things for $1 USD for a costume. The developers have said they intend to keep it cosmetic only and not pay to win. Currency is also changed from mana to in game coins creating a slower climb to currency becoming trivial. DDE includes all of the original's DLC minus some of the holiday maps (for now).As of this writing, there are many bugs that plague this new version from summoner pets jumping off cliffs to hotkeys being unbound with every map. The bright side of this is the new patching system is far better than before. Like Guild Wars, they can patch small things with minimal downtime server-side.The UI is far more suitable for mouse and keyboard in this iteration, albeit a bit clunky at the moment. It's still more customizable than the original DD. Controller support on the other hand is clunkier on this version. Hopefully these quality of life things will get ironed out with time.So for those who own the original and enjoyed it DDE really only offers a chance at a fresh start with less hackers, a few new maps and a promise of easier distribution of content with the new software for the future. For $6 USD, it could pass for DLC-lite for prior owners. For those who haven't tried the original DD or don't own most of the DLC for the original, even the normal price of $20 USD is a worthwhile investment. However, for normal price, prior owners who own all the DLC might want to hold off picking this up until there's more meat on the bone.I really wish there was a way to just post a review without a recommendation. For DDE, it's less black and white and more 'depends'. There's potential in DDE as something to hold out until DD2, but for now it's only for those looking for a fresh start or those who haven't tried DD, a fantastic tower defense game. The tech behind the patching system is a very solid foundation for future content, hopefully TrendyNet will support DDE with more content before the inevitable DD2 hits the market."
